TITLE: ⏰ Save your time and schedule your notebook like a script!
TEXT:
⏰ Save your time and schedule your notebook like a script!


To schedule your Jupyter Notebook using Papermill in naas.ai, you just need to add this simple formula👇.

import naas
naas.scheduler.add(cron="0 * * * *") ← this cron argument is the standard syntax worldwide. It means every hour in that case.

Press play ▶️ and your notebook will be sent to the Naas "⚡️Production folder".

Every time your notebook is executed, a record will be stored in this folder so you can access it if it fails.

Try now following this video: https://lnkd.in/erXctqWD

Thanks, Caleb Keller for the inspiration for my post!

Spread the open source love always 💚

TITLE: What are you waiting for to start data science? Are you scared?
TEXT:
What are you waiting for to start data science? Are you scared?
The truth is…


I was scared too. I knew it was an important thing to do in my career but I didn’t know where to start… Luckily I had a brother Jérémy Ravenel to help me succeed.
Here are the tips he gave me to get started:

✅ Focus on achievable goals
Start working on a simple project that matters to you. Split the project into steps, and appreciate each time go to the next.

✅ Organize your idea before doing anything
For this, I suggest using the simple framework we use at Naas: Input/Model/Output

✅ Google everything
You can literally ask “How to read excel in python?” and start from there (sorry my dear 🇫🇷 compatriot, it works best in English).
No need to have prior knowledge of any programming language.

✅ Use Jupyter Notebook Project Jupyter, the most popular data science interface
→ Before, there was only Anaconda distribution, on your computer (some tech setup required)
→ Now, there is naas.ai, on your browser (no setup required) 🙈😇

Naas comes with a bunch of templates that are ready to use, so it’s even easier to start now.
Check out the link in the first comment,
and let me know what you think?

Thanks a lot 🙂🙏🏻

TITLE: ⚙️ Managing DateTime in data is a pain in the a🍑🍑
TEXT:
⚙️ Managing DateTime in data is a pain in the a🍑🍑

If you work with Python, DateTime format is your best friend!

With a simple date, you can analyse your data weekly, monthly, quarterly, and beyond.

Mastering it can help you grow your business remarkably. But to achieve it, you need to know how to manipulate it.

I personally spent time learning by myself with the help of many stackoverflow forums. Today, it is time to share some tips about Python with you. 👇


First you need to master d3-time-format in Python.
To do so, I learnt from this useful GitHub documentation https://lnkd.in/e3U3HXVz. We will learn that “2021-31-12” is “%Y-%m-%d”

Then, simply use the formulas (notebooks template’s are available in first comment):
- to convert a string date to a datetime object to another string date : strptime(date_string, current_format).strftime(new_format)
- to convert pandas series to datetime series to another datetime format : df[col_date] = pd.to_datetime(df[col_date], current_format).dt.strftime(new_format)

Did you know this?

Feel free to share other tips! I am always happy to learn 😄 🙏


Want more tips? Do not hesitate to like, comment and share this post! Don't forget to star the GitHub repository!

TITLE: 💡 Data science is about making data useful.
TEXT:
💡 Data science is about making data useful.
And there is a simple way to do that.

Here is how :

I have been working on data science projects for 5+ years, without even knowing it.
I switched from Excel to Python to fix some problems I had, tested a lot of things, failed a lot of times.

But I also learned that it’s not about coding, it’s about organizing ideas.

Here is a simple framework that worked every single time.
👇

-> Define your inputs clearly
List the tools you want to use, how to access them, what are the specific part of the data you want to get.
-> Think about how to model
Define the rules / transformation you want to apply to your data.
-> Design the outputs
A table, a graph, an Excel spreadsheet or an email...think very precisely about what is making sense for you or your audience.

In short, if you work with data, keep this framework in mind :
- Input
- Model
- Output
It will help you see clear and stay focus!

In a next post, I will show you a template on NBA bets done by one of our community members.

I’m going to try posting more regularly so if you want to support : any like or comment is welcome.⚡️

See you!

PS: I’m not alone in this data science journey, the project I’m working on (naas.ai) is about making the field much more accessible to anyone.

You can join us too, even if you are not a tech - I’m not 😉 (the link to our Slack is in the first comment)

TITLE: Dans ma vie professionnelle, je n'ai jamais aimé 😤 :
TEXT:
Dans ma vie professionnelle, je n'ai jamais aimé 😤 :
- faire des tâches répétitives 
- passer du temps sur une tache sans valeur ajoutée
- finir tard (et louper les happy hours 🍻)

Alors, je me suis mis à automatiser mon travail.
J'ai démarré sur Excel, puis VBA et enfin Python 🐍

Evidemment, je n'ai pas appris ça tout seul, il a fallu :
- de bons mentors*
- beaucoup de recherches sur internet
- et plus de 4 ans de mise en pratique chez CashStory

Aujourd'hui, toute cette expérience et méthode, on souhaite la partager avec vous.

C'est pourquoi, on a décidé de créer notre parcours de formation.

Au programme : optimiser l'usage d'Excel, passer d'Excel à Python, scripting sur des Jupyter notebooks (utilisé à 99% dans la data-science).

World Situation Room : Après un mois de confinement, on en est où ?

Pour commencer merci pour vous nombreux retours, plus de 13 000 visiteurs pour 100 000 pages vues !

Pour y voir plus clair, des nouvelles améliorations sont disponibles : https://imf.to/WRSFR

Un grand merci à Carlos G., Marco Micozzi, Christophe Delmotte, Jordan Lorho, Clément Queste, Clément JANET-MAITRE, Jon BARANOFF, Quentin HELIOT, Juliette GENIN, Louise HERPSONT HORRILLO et bien d’autres pour leurs retours pertinents qui nous ont permis de faire évoluer cette application.

TITLE: COVID-19, Economie : Des chiffres dans tous les sens mais on ne retient rien
TEXT:
COVID-19, Economie : Des chiffres dans tous les sens mais on ne retient rien
 
 
Avec mon équipe, nous avons l’habitude de travailler
avec des données compliquées pour les rendre simples et accessibles à tous.
Nous avons remarqué que les données sanitaires et économiques n’étaient pas
regroupées dans un même endroit. 
 
C’est pour cela que nous avons lancé la semaine
dernière, l’application publique : World Situation Room
https://imf.to/WRSFR .
 
Le but est de donner accès au plus grand nombre à des
informations diffusées sur les différents canaux. Nous les regroupons et nous
les restituions de manière simple pour tous.
 
Avec plus de 3 000 visiteurs en 2 jours et grâce à
vos nombreux retours, nous allons continuer à faire évoluer ce projet avec
vous.
 
Pour soutenir le projet, partagez à vos contacts et
abonnez-vous,
 
Restez chez vous et prenez soin de vous,
 
#restezchezvous #stayathome 
CashStory | Augmented Financial Analytics
